         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne, August 14, 1886. ¶  ¶ Sir—All the species of pimelia ¶  contain an acrid principle, which in some is so strongly developed as to render the bark available as a vesicant. One of the species ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">86.08.14</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">To Otto Tepper</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found; the text given here is from 'A noxious plant', </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">South Australian advertiser</seg>
                     <seg style="">, 20 August 1886, p. 7 (B86.08.09), a 'Letter to the Editor' from Tepper and two letters that he enclosed with this, M's letter to him and, printed before this, a letter dated 19 August from an unnamed correspondent in Yorketown, SA, enclosing a specimen of a plant with suspected toxic properties.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>Melbourne, August 14, 1886.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Sir—All the species of pimelia<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Typesetter's error for </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Pimelea</seg>
                     <seg style="">?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> contain an acrid principle, which in some is so strongly developed as to render the bark available as a vesicant. One of the species with the strongest burning acridity is <name key="Pimelia%20struta">Pimelia struta</name>,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Typesetter's error for </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Pimelea stricta</seg>
                     <seg style="">?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> which I noticed as long ago as 1848, on sandy ground, between Port Adelaide and your city. As pointed out in former writings of mine, the bark of several of our Australian species of pimelia can medicinally be substituted for that of the European daphnes;<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See, for example, B72.07.01, B80.13.07 and subsequent editions under </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Thymelaea tinctoria</seg>
                     <seg style="">;</seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; "> </seg>
                     <seg style="">B69.02.03.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> both genera belonging to one order of plants, that of Thymeleae. It is thus evident that the intermixture of pimelias of any kind into pastures is injurious to the herds or flocks, which in dearth of fodder, particularly during seasons of drought, might feed extensively on these acrid pimelias also. Where they prevail the ground should be ploughed up and sown with strong grasses and fodder-herbs, which would suffocate the pimelias, or prevent at all events them from spreading copiously.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">Very respectfully yours</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">F. Von Mueller</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">J. G. O. Tepper, Esq, F.L.S.</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Pimelia%20struta">Pimelia struta</name>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
